#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "Spec File Reference"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Spec files are text files that contain RPM directives and macro definitions, "
"which are used to build an RPM package. The RPM directives and macros are "
"divided into a number of sections. Each of these sections is delimited with "
"a <code>%</code> marker. For example, the build section starts with "
"<code>%build</code>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid "A typical spec file consists of approximately five sections:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "Preamble"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The preamble describes the basic information on the package, for example "
"name, version, license, and so on."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "Build section"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The build section includes instructions, which are used to build and prepare "
"the package for installation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "Scriptlets"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The scriptlets define commands used to install, upgrade, or uninstall the "
"package."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "Manifest"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The manifest section includes a list of packaged files and their permissions."
""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "Changelog"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The changelog section consists of a list of changes made to the package."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "Spec File Directives"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Directives in a spec file are defined using a simple syntax of a tag name, a "
"colon, and a value:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<replaceable>TagName</replaceable>: <replaceable>value</replaceable> \n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, the following directive sets the package version to 1.15:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Version: 1.15 \n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The name of the item is not case sensitive, so tag names of <option>version</"
"option>, <option>Version</option>, or <option>VERSION</option> all set the "
"same value. This syntax works for most settings, including <option>Name</"
"option>, <option>Release</option>, and so on."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "Spec File Macros"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In addition to the spec file directive syntax, you can define macros using "
"the RPM <code>%global</code> syntax. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "%global major 2 \n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The example above defines a macro named <code>major</code> with a value of "
"<code>2</code>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Once defined, you can access macros using the syntax <code>%{macro_name}</"
"code> or just <code>%macro_name</code>. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "source: %{name}-%{version}.tar.gz \n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "Spec File Comments"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To include comments in the spec file, use a <code>#</code> character at the "
"start of the line. That way, the line will be ignored by RPM."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Because macros are expanded first, do not insert any multiline macros in a "
"comment. If you want to comment out a line with a macro, double the percent "
"signs (<code>%%</code>) as in the following example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "# %%configure\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Also, do not use inline comments (\"#\") on the same line after a script "
"command. <remark> '''Warning:''' In spec files, don't use in-line comments "
"(a \"#\" comment on the same line after a command), and don't put macros "
"(words beginning with \"%\") in a comment unless you quote the \"%\" as "
"\"%%\". Macros can cause failures if they are in a comment, because they are "
"always expanded (even when in a comment) and they can expand to multiple "
"lines. This is true for %prep, %build, and so on. </remark>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "Spec File Example"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Below is an example of a spec file from the <package>eject</package> package "
"in &MAJOROSVER;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"Summary: A program that ejects removable media using software control\n"
"Name: eject\n"
"Version: 2.1.5\n"
"Release: 11%{dist}\n"
"License: GPL\n"
"Source: http://metalab.unc.edu/pub/Linux/utils/disk-management/%{name}-"
"%{version}.tar.gz\n"
"Source1: eject.pam\n"
"Patch1: eject-2.1.1-verbose.patch\n"
"Patch2: eject-timeout.patch\n"
"Patch3: eject-2.1.5-opendevice.patch\n"
"Patch4: eject-2.1.5-spaces.patch\n"
"Patch5: eject-2.1.5-lock.patch\n"
"Patch6: eject-2.1.5-umount.patch\n"
"URL: http://www.pobox.com/~tranter\n"
"ExcludeArch: s390 s390x\n"
"BuildRequires: gettext\n"
"BuildRequires: automake\n"
"BuildRequires: autoconf\n"
"BuildRequires: libtool\n"
" \n"
"%description\n"
"The eject program allows the user to eject removable media (typically\n"
"CD-ROMs, floppy disks or Iomega Jaz or Zip disks) using software\n"
"control. Eject can also control some multi-disk CD changers and even\n"
"some devices' auto-eject features.\n"
" \n"
"Install eject if you'd like to eject removable media using software\n"
"control.\n"
" \n"
"%prep\n"
"%setup -q -n %{name}\n"
"%patch1 -p1 -b .verbose\n"
"%patch2 -p1 -b .timeout\n"
"%patch3 -p0 -b .opendevice\n"
"%patch4 -p0 -b .spaces\n"
"%patch5 -p0 -b .lock\n"
"%patch6 -p1 -b .umount\n"
" \n"
"%build\n"
"%configure\n"
"make\n"
" \n"
"%install\n"
"rm -rf %{buildroot}\n"
" \n"
"make DESTDIR=%{buildroot} install\n"
" \n"
"# pam stuff\n"
"install -m 755 -d %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/pam.d\n"
"install -m 644 %{SOURCE1} %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/pam.d/%{name}\n"
"install -m 755 -d %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/security/console.apps/\n"
"echo \"FALLBACK=true\" &gt; %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/security/console."
"apps/%{name}\n"
" \n"
"install -m 755 -d %{buildroot}/%{_sbindir}\n"
"pushd %{buildroot}/%{_bindir}\n"
"mv eject ../sbin\n"
"ln -s consolehelper eject\n"
"popd\n"
" \n"
"%find_lang %{name}\n"
" \n"
"%files -f %{name}.lang\n"
"%doc README TODO COPYING ChangeLog\n"
"%attr(644,root,root) %{_sysconfdir}/security/console.apps/*\n"
"%attr(644,root,root) %{_sysconfdir}/pam.d/*\n"
"%{_bindir}/*\n"
"%{_sbindir}/*\n"
"%{_mandir}/man1/*\n"
" \n"
"%changelog\n"
"* Wed Apr 02 2008 Zdenek Prikryl &lt;zprikryl at, redhat.com&gt; 2.1.5-11\n"
"- Added check if device is hotpluggable\n"
"- Resolves #438610"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The example above shows the usage of some of the directives and macros in a "
"spec file. Refer to <xref linkend=\"chap-Packagers_Guide-Spec_File_Reference-"
"Preamble\" /> for a detailed description of the directives and macros."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "Spec File Preamble"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This section include a list with descriptions of some of the more frequently "
"used directives in spec files."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>Name: <replaceable>name</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Name:</option> tag defines the (base) name of the package. This "
"name must follow the <ulink url=\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging/"
"NamingGuidelines\">Fedora Package Naming Guidelines</ulink>. Also, this name "
"should match the spec file name. In many cases, the name will be in all "
"lower case. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Name: eject"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Elsewhere in the spec file, you can refer to the name using the macro "
"<option>%{name}</option>. That way, if the name changes, the new name will "
"be used by those other locations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>Version: <replaceable>version</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Version</option> tag defines the upstream version number. If the "
"version is non-numeric (that is it contains tags that are not numbers or "
"digits), you may need to include the additional non-numeric characters in "
"the <option>Release</option> tag. If upstream uses full dates to distinguish "
"versions, consider using version numbers of the form <code>yy.mm[.dd]</code> "
"(so a <code>2008-05-01</code> release becomes <code>8.05</code>). See <ulink "
"url=\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging/"
"NamingGuidelines#Package_Versioning\">Fedora Package Naming Guidelines</"
"ulink> for more information. An example of the <option>Version</option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Version: 2.1.5"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Elsewhere in the spec file, refer to the tag value as %{version}. That way, "
"if the tag value changes, the new value will be used by those other "
"locations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>Release: <replaceable>release</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Release</option> tag defines the value of the package's version. "
"The initial release will typically be defined as <option>1%{?dist}</option>. "
"After the initial release, increment the number every time a new package is "
"released for the same version of software. If a new version of the packaged "
"software is released, the <option>Version</option> tag should be changed to "
"reflect the new software version, and the <option>Release</option> tag "
"should be reset to <option>1</option>. See <ulink url=\"http://fedoraproject."
"org/wiki/Packaging/NamingGuidelines#Package_Versioning\">Fedora Package "
"Naming Guidelines</ulink> for more information. Refer to the <ulink url="
"\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging/DistTag\">Fedora Dist Tag "
"Guidelines</ulink> for a description of the <code>dist</code> tag, which is "
"not required but can be useful. An example of the <option>Release</option> "
"tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Release: 11%{dist}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Elsewhere in the spec file, refer to the tag value as %{release}. That way, "
"if the tag value changes, the new value will be used by those other "
"locations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>Summary: <replaceable>summary</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Summary</option> tag defines a brief, one-line summary of the "
"package. Do not use a period at the end of the summary. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Summary: A program that ejects removable media using software control"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>Group: <replaceable>group</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Group</option> tag defines a package group, which the package is "
"a part of. The tag must define a previously existing group, for example "
"<option>Applications/Engineering</option>. To display a complete list of "
"existing groups, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>less /usr/share/doc/rpm-*/GROUPS</command>\n"
"              "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you create a <package><replaceable>package</replaceable>-doc</package> "
"sub-package with documentation, use the group <option>Documentation</option>."
" An example of the <option>Group</option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Group: System Environment/Base"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Group tag is deprecated"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<application>RPM</application> in &MAJOROSVER; does not require the presence "
"of the <code>Group</code> tag in the spec file. If the tag is defined, it "
"will be ignored. The package groups of the <application>yum</application> "
"application are used on a &MAJOROSVER; system as the relevant source of "
"information on which group is the package a part of."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>License: <replaceable>license</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>License</option> tag defines the license of the packaged "
"software. Use a standard abbreviation, for example <option>GPLv2+</option>. "
"The definition of the license should be specific; for example do not use "
"<option>GPL</option> or <option>GPLv2</option> when the license is in fact "
"GPL version 2 or greater, that is <option>GPLv2+</option>. You can list "
"multiple licenses in the tag by combining them with words <code>and</code> "
"and <code>or</code>, for example <option>GPLv2 and BSD</option>. Refer to "
"the <ulink url=\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Licensing\">Fedora Licensing "
"Document</ulink> and the <ulink url=\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/"
"Packaging/LicensingGuidelines\">Licensing Guidelines</ulink> for more "
"information on this topic."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Do not use the tag <option>Copyright</option> in place of the "
"<option>License</option> tag. An example of the <option>License</option> tag:"
""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "License: GPL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>URL: <replaceable>URL</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>URL</option> tag defines the URL with more information about the "
"program, for example the project website. This tag does not define where the "
"original source code came from, use the the tag <option>Source</option> for "
"that purpose. An example of the <option>URL</option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "URL: http://www.pobox.com/~tranter"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<option>Source<replaceable>0</replaceable>: <replaceable>URL</replaceable> </"
"option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Source</option> tag defines a URL for the compressed archive "
"containing the (original) unmodified source code, as upstream released it. "
"The tag <option>Source</option> is the same as the tag <option>Source0</"
"option>. Because a full URL should be provided with this tag, its basename "
"can be then used when looking in the <filename class=\"directory\">SOURCES/</"
"filename> directory. If possible, add <option>%{name}</option> and "
"<option>%{version}</option> to the URL."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The tag <option>Source</option> and the tag <option>URL</option> are used "
"for different purposes. Typically, they are both URLs, but the <option>URL</"
"option> tag points to the project website, while the <option>Source</option> "
"tag points to the actual file containing the source code."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When downloading the source code, consider using a client that preserves the "
"upstream timestamps, such as <application>wget</application>. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>wget -N <replaceable>URL</replaceable></command>\n"
"              "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you are using <application>curl</application>, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>curl -R <replaceable>URL</replaceable></command>\n"
"              "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If there is more than one source, name them <option>Source1</option>, "
"<option>Source2</option>, and so on. If you are adding whole new files in "
"addition to the unmodified sources, you can list each of them as sources as "
"well, but list them <emphasis>after</emphasis> the unmodified sources. "
"Remember to include a copy of each of these sources in any source package "
"you create. For information on exceptions to this rule, such as when using "
"revision control system, upstream using prohibited code, and so on, refer to "
"the <ulink url=\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging/SourceURL\">Fedora "
"Source URL Guidelines</ulink>. An example of the <option>Source</option> tag:"
""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Source1: eject.pam"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<option>Patch<replaceable>0</replaceable>: <replaceable>file_name</"
"replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Patch<replaceable>0</replaceable>:</option> tag defines the name "
"of the first patch that you will apply to the source code. If you need to "
"patch the files after they have been uncompressed, edit the files, save "
"their differences as a <emphasis>patch</emphasis> file in the <filename "
"class=\"directory\">~/rpmbuild/SOURCES/</filename> directory. Patches should "
"make only one logical change, so it is likely to have multiple patch files. "
"If there is more than one source, name them <option>Patch1</option>, "
"<option>Patch2</option>, and so on. An example of the <option>Patch1</"
"option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Patch1: eject-2.1.1-verbose.patch"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>BuildArch: <replaceable>architecture</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>BuildArch</option> tag is used to define the build architecture "
"of the package. If you are packaging files that are architecture-"
"independent, for example shell scripts, data files, and so on, use "
"<option>BuildArch: noarch</option>. In this case, the architecture for the "
"binary RPM will be <code>noarch</code>. An example of the <option>BuildArch</"
"option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "BuildArch: noarch"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>ExcludeArch: <replaceable>architecture</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>ExcludeArch</option> tag defines any excluded build architecture."
" If the package does not successfully compile, build or work on an "
"architecture, then the architecture should be defined in the "
"<option>ExcludeArch</option> tag. An example of the <option>ExcludeArch</"
"option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "ExcludeArch: i386"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>BuildRoot: <replaceable>build root</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>BuildRoot</option> defines the location of the files "
"<emphasis>installed</emphasis> during the <code>%install</code> process, "
"which happens after the <code>%build</code> compilation process. In a "
"typical situation, leave this line alone: under the usual &MAJOROSVER; "
"setup, a macro that will create a new special subdirectory in the <filename "
"class=\"directory\">/var/tmp/</filename> directory will be used. Newer "
"versions of RPM ignore this value, and instead place the build root in "
"<code>%{_topdir}/BUILDROOT/</code>. An example of the <option>BuildRoot</"
"option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "BuildRoot: %{_tmppath}/%{name}-%{version}-%{release}-root"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "The BuildRoot tag is deprecated"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<application>RPM</application> in &MAJOROSVER; does not require the presence "
"of the <code>BuildRoot</code> tag in the spec file. If the tag is defined, "
"it will be ignored. The provided buildroot will automatically be cleaned "
"before commands in <code>%install</code> are called."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<option>BuildRequires: <replaceable>requirements</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>BuildRequires</option> tag defines a comma-separated list of "
"packages required for building (or compiling) the software. These are "
"<emphasis>not</emphasis> automatically determined, so you must include every "
"package needed to build the software."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"There are a few packages that are so common in builds that you do not need "
"to mention them, such as <package>gcc</package>. Refer to the <ulink url="
"\"http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Packaging/Guidelines\">Fedora Packaging "
"Guidelines</ulink> for a complete list of the packages you may omit."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can use more than one BuildRequires tag, in which case all BuildRequires "
"tags they are all required for building. If necessary, you can also specify "
"a minimum version of the package, for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "ocaml &gt;= 3.08\n"
"              "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<remark>If you need file /EGGS, you can get its package by running \"rpm -qf "
"/EGGS\"; if EGGS is a program, you determine its package quickly by running "
"\"rpm -qf `which EGGS`\". </remark>Try to specify only the minimal set of "
"packages necessary to properly build the package, since each one will slow "
"down a <emphasis>mock</emphasis>-based build. <remark>Watch out: Some "
"applications permanently disable functions if their package isn't detected "
"during the build; in those cases you may need to include those additional "
"packages. If you have trouble figuring out this list, the \"auto-br-"
"rpmbuild\" command (from the auto-buildrequires package) may be helpful.</"
"remark> An example of the <option>BuildRequires</option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "BuildRequires: gettext"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>Requires: <replaceable>requirements</replaceable> </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>Requires</option> tag defines a comma-separate list of packages "
"that are required when the software is installed. Remember that the list of "
"packages for the <option>Requires</option> tag and the "
"<option>BuildRequires</option> tag are independent: a package may be in one "
"list but not the other, or it can be in both. The dependencies of binary "
"packages are in many cases automatically detected by <application>pmbuild</"
"application>, so it is often the case that you do not need to specify the "
"<option>Requires</option> tag at all. But if you want to highlight some "
"specific packages as being required, or require a package that RPM cannot "
"detect should be required, then add it to the <option>Requires</option> tag. "
"An example of the <option>Requires</option> tag:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requires: gettext"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<option>%description <replaceable>description text</replaceable></option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%description</option> directive defines a longer, multiline "
"description of the package. All lines must be 80 characters long or less. "
"Blank lines are assumed to separate paragraphs. Remember that some graphical "
"user interface installation programs will reformat paragraphs. Lines that "
"start with whitespace, such as a space or tab, will be treated as "
"preformatted text and displayed as is, normally with a fixed-width font. An "
"example of the <option>%description</option> directive:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"%description\n"
"The eject program allows the user to eject removable media (typically\n"
"CD-ROMs, floppy disks or Iomega Jaz or Zip disks) using software\n"
"control. Eject can also control some multi-disk CD changers and even\n"
"some devices' auto-eject features.\n"
"\n"
"Install eject if you'd like to eject removable media using software\n"
"control."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>%prep </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%prep</option> directive defines script commands to "
"<emphasis>prepare</emphasis> the software before the start of the building "
"process. In a typical situation, the definition is similar to <code>%setup -"
"q</code>. For example, if the source file unpacks into <filename>name</"
"filename>, the definition is <code>%setup -q -n name</code>. <remark>See the "
"\"%prep\" section below for more.</remark> An example of the <option>%prep</"
"option> directive:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "%prep\n"
"%setup -q -n %{name}\n"
"%patch1 -p1 -b .verbose"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>%build </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%build</option> directive defines script commands to build "
"(compile) the software, that is, to get it ready for installing. "
"<remark>Typically, software includes instructions on how to build it. See "
"the \"%build\" section below for more.</remark> An example of the %build "
"directive:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "%build\n"
"%configure\n"
"make"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>%check </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%check</option> directive defines script commands to self-test "
"the program. The self-tests are run after <option>%build</option> and before "
"<option>%install</option>, so the <option>%check</option> directive should "
"be placed accordingly between the directives mentioned above. Usually, the "
"<option>%check</option> directive contains the <command>make test</command> "
"or <command>make check</command> commands. These commands are separated from "
"the <option>%build</option> directive so that users can skip the self-test "
"process, if they desire."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "%check\n"
"make check\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>%install </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%install</option> directive defines script commands to "
"<emphasis>install</emphasis> the software. The script commands copy the "
"build files from the build directory <option>%{_builddir}</option> (usually "
"a subdirectory of the directory <filename class=\"directory\">~/rpmbuild/"
"BUILD/</filename>) into the build root directory <option>%{buildroot}</"
"option> (usually a subdirectory of the directory <filename class="
"\"directory\">/var/tmp/</filename>). <remark>See the \"%install\" section "
"below for more.</remark> An example of the<option>%install</option> "
"directive:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"%install\n"
"rm -rf %{buildroot}\n"
"\n"
"make DESTDIR=%{buildroot} install\n"
"\n"
"install -m 755 -d %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/pam.d\n"
"install -m 644 %{SOURCE1} %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/pam.d/%{name}\n"
"install -m 755 -d %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/security/console.apps/\n"
"echo \"FALLBACK=true\" &gt; %{buildroot}/%{_sysconfdir}/security/console."
"apps/%{name}\n"
"\n"
"install -m 755 -d %{buildroot}/%{_sbindir}\n"
"pushd %{buildroot}/%{_bindir}\n"
"mv eject ../sbin\n"
"ln -s consolehelper eject\n"
"popd\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>%clean </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%clean</option> directive defines instructions on how to clean "
"out the build root. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "%clean\n"
"rm -rf %{buildroot}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#, no-c-format
msgid "The %clean directive is deprecated"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<application>RPM</application> in &MAJOROSVER; does not require the presence "
"of the <code>%clean</code> directive in the spec file. If the tag is "
"defined, it will be ignored."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>%files </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%files</option> directive contains a list of files in the "
"package to be installed.<remark> See the \"%files\" section below for more</"
"remark> For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid "%files -f %{name}.lang\n"
"            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>%changelog </option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <option>%changelog</option> directive defines changes in the package. "
"<remark>Use the format example above.</remark> For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"%changelog\n"
"* Wed Apr 02 2008 John Due &lt;jdoe at example.com&gt; 2.1.5-11\n"
"- Added check if device is hotpluggable\n"
"- Resolves #438610\n"
msgstr ""

